    <h2>History of Beer</h2>
    <div class="content" style="display:none">
        <p>Man has been brewing beer for as long as he is farming. Agriculture developed in the fertile lands of the eastern Mediterranean about 8,000 years ago when wild cereals were ‘tamed’ and cultivated for the first time. Grain was eaten as a porridge, ground to make bread and brewed as beer. Brewing and bread making developed in tandem and beer, sometimes called ‘liquid bread’, was an integral part of man’s diet, being both nutritious and thirst quenching.</p>

        <p>As agriculture spread, so too did brewing. Ireland’s first farmers settled here about 5,000 years ago and these people were our first brewers.</p>

        <p>Since these early days, a strong brewing tradition has developed throughout Ireland, initially by retail brewers, the owners of taverns and alehouses who brewed beer for sale on their own premises. In the 1720s a dark beer known as porter was developed in London and quickly became the popular in Ireland. Large volumes were imported from England through the middle decades of the century.</p>

        <p>Irish entrepreneurs saw the potential and a number of commercial breweries were established in the later 1700s. Tea and coffee had not yet become accessible to the majority of the population and as drinking water was of poor quality, beer provided a safe and sterile drink which was enjoyed by all.</p>

        <p>Throughout the 1800s and 1900s, brewing in Ireland really came into its own with the
        founding of many famous breweries - most of which are still in operation today. Check out our Beer Timeline for a list of key dates.</p>
