    <h2>Craft Beer Jargon</h2>
    <div class="content" style="display:none">
        <p><strong>Craft Beer</strong>
        Beer from a craft brewery. That’s an independent brewery with an annual production of no more than six million barrels. The brewery uses traditional malting methods to make its tipples.</p>

        <p><strong>ABV</strong>
        Alcohol by Volume: the percentage of your beer. 4.5%: you’ll feel OK in the morning. 6.6%: wow—that went fuzzy fast. 11%: HELLO MOM I LOVE YOU.</p>

        <p><strong>Malt</strong>
        Fermented grains, usually barley. They’re the base of all beer, and they have a rich, sweet, earthy flavor.</p>

        <p><strong>Hops</strong>
        The flowers which give beer its characteristic bitterness, as well as a heady floral aroma. Hoppy beers are very trendy amongst craft breweries, for better or for worse.</p>

        <p><strong>IBU</strong>
        International Bitterness Units. How bitter, and therefore how hoppy, a beer is. Lagers start at five IBUs. IPAs tend to be around 40-60. Much higher than that, and you can’t really tell the difference.</p>

        <p><strong>Pale Ale</strong>
        Covers a vast range of beers made with pale malt. Includes English bitters, plus (in increasing strength of flavor and maltiness) blonde, amber/red and brown ales.</p>

        <p><strong>IPA</strong>
        India Pale Ale. Originally brewed by the English for consumption in South Asia, they’ve since been adopted by American craft breweries and have spearheaded the US craft movement. Hyper-floral and hoppy.</p>

        <p><strong>Lager</strong>
        Pale, golden. You know the stuff.</p>

        <p><strong>Wheat beer</strong>
        Brewed with wheat as well as malt to give a light, slightly sour flavor.</p>

        <p><strong>Saison</strong>
        Belgian farmhouse-style pale ale. Bubbly, fruity and spiced.</p>

        <p><strong>Porter / Stout</strong>
        Strong, dark-brown or black beer. Smoky and rich. Often tastes of coffee or chocolate.</p>

        <p><strong>“Session” beer</strong>
        An easy-to-drink beer of about 4.5% ABV. Quaffable over an extended “session” without the need to go be sick in a bush</p>
